26/* Note: In MPFR math functions, even if UBF code is not called first,
27 we may still need to handle special values NaN and infinities here.
28 Indeed, for MAXR * MAXR + (-inf), even though this is a special case,
29 the computation will also generate an overflow due to MAXR * MAXR,
30 so that UBF code will be called anyway (except if special cases are
31 detected and handled separately, but for polynomial, this should not
32 be needed). */
33
34/* This function does not change the flags. */
35static void
36mpfr_init_get_zexp (mpz_ptr ez, mpfr_srcptr x)
37{
38 mpz_init (ez);
39
40 if (MPFR_IS_UBF (x))
41 mpz_set (ez, MPFR_ZEXP (x));
42 else
43 {
44 mp_limb_t e_limb[MPFR_EXP_LIMB_SIZE];
45 mpfr_t e;
46 int inex;
47 MPFR_SAVE_EXPO_DECL (expo);
48
49 /* TODO: Once this has been tested, optimize based on whether
50 _MPFR_EXP_FORMAT <= 3. */
51 MPFR_TMP_INIT1 (e_limb, e, sizeof (mpfr_exp_t) * CHAR_BIT);
52 MPFR_SAVE_EXPO_MARK (expo);
53 MPFR_DBGRES (inex = mpfr_set_exp_t (e, MPFR_GET_EXP (x), MPFR_RNDN));
54 MPFR_ASSERTD (inex == 0);
55 MPFR_DBGRES (inex = mpfr_get_z (ez, e, MPFR_RNDN));
56 MPFR_ASSERTD (inex == 0);
57 MPFR_SAVE_EXPO_FREE (expo);
58 }
59}
60
61/* Exact product. The number a is assumed to have enough allocated memory,
62 where the trailing bits are regarded as being part of the input numbers
63 (no reallocation is attempted and no check is performed as MPFR_TMP_INIT
64 could have been used). The arguments b and c may actually be UBF numbers
65 (mpfr_srcptr can be seen a bit like void *, but is stronger).
66 This function does not change the flags, except in case of NaN. */
67void
68mpfr_ubf_mul_exact (mpfr_ubf_ptr a, mpfr_srcptr b, mpfr_srcptr c)
69{
70 MPFR_LOG_FUNC
71 (("b[%Pu]=%.*Rg c[%Pu]=%.*Rg",
72 mpfr_get_prec (b), mpfr_log_prec, b,
73 mpfr_get_prec (c), mpfr_log_prec, c),
74 ("a[%Pu]=%.*Rg",
75 mpfr_get_prec (a), mpfr_log_prec, a));
76
77 MPFR_ASSERTD ((mpfr_ptr) a != b);
78 MPFR_ASSERTD ((mpfr_ptr) a != c);
79 MPFR_SIGN (a) = MPFR_MULT_SIGN (MPFR_SIGN (b), MPFR_SIGN (c));
80
81 if (MPFR_ARE_SINGULAR (b, c))
82 {
83 if (MPFR_IS_NAN (b) || MPFR_IS_NAN (c))
84 MPFR_SET_NAN (a);
85 else if (MPFR_IS_INF (b))
86 {
87 if (MPFR_NOTZERO (c))
88 MPFR_SET_INF (a);
89 else
90 MPFR_SET_NAN (a);
91 }
92 else if (MPFR_IS_INF (c))
93 {
94 if (!MPFR_IS_ZERO (b))
95 MPFR_SET_INF (a);
96 else
97 MPFR_SET_NAN (a);
98 }
99 else
100 {
101 MPFR_ASSERTD (MPFR_IS_ZERO(b) || MPFR_IS_ZERO(c));
102 MPFR_SET_ZERO (a);
103 }
104 }
105 else
106 {
107 mpfr_exp_t e;
108 mp_size_t bn, cn;
109 mpfr_limb_ptr ap;
110 mp_limb_t u, v;
111 int m;
112
113 /* Note about the code below: For the choice of the precision of
114 * the result a, one could choose PREC(b) + PREC(c), instead of
115 * taking whole limbs into account, but in most cases where one
116 * would gain one limb, one would need to copy the significand
117 * instead of a no-op (see the mul.c code).
118 * But in the case MPFR_LIMB_MSB (u) == 0, if the result fits in
119 * an-1 limbs, one could actually do
120 * mpn_rshift (ap, ap, k, GMP_NUMB_BITS - 1)
121 * instead of
122 * mpn_lshift (ap, ap, k, 1)
123 * to gain one limb (and reduce the precision), replacing a shift
124 * by another one. Would this be interesting?
125 */
126
127 bn = MPFR_LIMB_SIZE (b);
128 cn = MPFR_LIMB_SIZE (c);
129
130 ap = MPFR_MANT (a);
131
132 if (bn == 1 && cn == 1)
133 {
134 umul_ppmm (ap[1], ap[0], MPFR_MANT(b)[0], MPFR_MANT(c)[0]);
135 if (ap[1] & MPFR_LIMB_HIGHBIT)
136 m = 0;
137 else
138 {
139 ap[1] = (ap[1] << 1) | (ap[0] >> (GMP_NUMB_BITS - 1));
140 ap[0] = ap[0] << 1;
141 m = 1;
142 }
143 }
144 else
145 {
146 u = (bn >= cn) ?
147 mpn_mul (ap, MPFR_MANT (b), bn, MPFR_MANT (c), cn) :
148 mpn_mul (ap, MPFR_MANT (c), cn, MPFR_MANT (b), bn);
149 if (MPFR_LIMB_MSB (u) == 0)
150 {
151 m = 1;
152 MPFR_DBGRES (v = mpn_lshift (ap, ap, bn + cn, 1));
153 MPFR_ASSERTD (v == 0);
154 }
155 else
156 m = 0;
157 }
158
159 if (! MPFR_IS_UBF (b) && ! MPFR_IS_UBF (c) &&
160 (e = MPFR_GET_EXP (b) + MPFR_GET_EXP (c) - m,
161 MPFR_EXP_IN_RANGE (e)))
162 {
163 MPFR_SET_EXP (a, e);
164 }
165 else
166 {
167 mpz_t be, ce;
168
169 mpz_init (MPFR_ZEXP (a));
170
171 /* This may involve copies of mpz_t, but exponents should not be
172 very large integers anyway. */
173 mpfr_init_get_zexp (be, b);
174 mpfr_init_get_zexp (ce, c);
175 mpz_add (MPFR_ZEXP (a), be, ce);
176 mpz_clear (be);
177 mpz_clear (ce);
178 mpz_sub_ui (MPFR_ZEXP (a), MPFR_ZEXP (a), m);
179 MPFR_SET_UBF (a);
180 }
181 }
182}
183
184int
185mpfr_ubf_exp_less_p (mpfr_srcptr x, mpfr_srcptr y)
186{
187 mpz_t xe, ye;
188 int c;
189
190 mpfr_init_get_zexp (xe, x);
191 mpfr_init_get_zexp (ye, y);
192 c = mpz_cmp (xe, ye) < 0;
193 mpz_clear (xe);
194 mpz_clear (ye);
195 return c;
196}

198/* Convert an mpz_t to an mpfr_exp_t, restricted to
199 the interval [MPFR_EXP_MIN,MPFR_EXP_MAX]. */
200mpfr_exp_t
201mpfr_ubf_zexp2exp (mpz_ptr ez)
202{
203 mp_size_t n;
204 mpfr_eexp_t e;
205 mpfr_t d;
206 int inex;
207 MPFR_SAVE_EXPO_DECL (expo);
208
209 n = ABSIZ (ez); /* limb size of ez */
210 if (n == 0)
211 return 0;
212
213 MPFR_SAVE_EXPO_MARK (expo);
214 mpfr_init2 (d, n * GMP_NUMB_BITS);
215 MPFR_DBGRES (inex = mpfr_set_z (d, ez, MPFR_RNDN));
216 MPFR_ASSERTD (inex == 0);
217 e = mpfr_get_exp_t (d, MPFR_RNDZ);
218 mpfr_clear (d);
219 MPFR_SAVE_EXPO_FREE (expo);
220 if (MPFR_UNLIKELY (e < MPFR_EXP_MIN))
221 return MPFR_EXP_MIN;
222 if (MPFR_UNLIKELY (e > MPFR_EXP_MAX))
223 return MPFR_EXP_MAX;
224 return e;
225}
226
227/* Return the difference of the exponents of x and y, restricted to
228 the interval [MPFR_EXP_MIN,MPFR_EXP_MAX]. */
229mpfr_exp_t
230mpfr_ubf_diff_exp (mpfr_srcptr x, mpfr_srcptr y)
231{
232 mpz_t xe, ye;
233 mpfr_exp_t e;
234
235 mpfr_init_get_zexp (xe, x);
236 mpfr_init_get_zexp (ye, y);
237 mpz_sub (xe, xe, ye);
238 mpz_clear (ye);
239 e = mpfr_ubf_zexp2exp (xe);
240 mpz_clear (xe);
241 return e;
242}
